.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Manual"
.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.RI [ script ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter that reads commands from standard
input or a script file and executes them.
It replicates the behavior of
.BR /bin/sh
for basic command execution.
.PP
If invoked with no arguments,
.B hsh
runs in interactive mode: it displays a prompt
.RB ( "$ " )
and waits for the user to type a command.
If standard input is not a terminal (pipe or file),
.B hsh
runs in non-interactive mode and reads commands silently.
.SH INVOCATION
.SS Interactive mode
.PP
.nf
$ ./hsh
($) /bin/ls
hsh main.c shell.h
($) exit
$
.fi
.SS Non-interactive mode
.PP
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
hsh main.c shell.h
$ cat commands.txt | ./hsh
.fi
.SH BUILTINS
.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell. The exit status is that of the last command executed.
.TP
.B env
Print the current environment, one variable per line in the form
.IR NAME=value .
.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
.PP
When a command is entered,
.B hsh
searches for an executable file in each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable, in order.
If the command contains a
.BR / ,
it is used as a path directly.
If the command is not found,
.B hsh
prints an error message to stderr:
.PP
.nf
./hsh: 1: command: not found
.fi
.PP
Commands are executed in a child process created with
.BR fork (2).
The child calls
.BR execve (2)
to replace itself with the target program.
The parent waits for the child to finish with
.BR wait (2).
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution.
.TP
.B 127
Command not found.
.TP
.B 1
General error (fork failure, etc.).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
Colon-separated list of directories searched for executables.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Run a command with its full path:
.PP
.nf
($) /bin/echo Hello, World!
Hello, World!
.fi
.PP
Run a command found in PATH:
.PP
.nf
($) ls -l /tmp
.fi
.PP
Print environment variables:
.PP
.nf
($) env
HOME=/root
PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin
...
.fi
.PP
Handle EOF (Ctrl+D):
.PP
.nf
($) ^D
$
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sh (1),
.BR bash (1),
.BR execve (2),
.BR fork (2),
.BR wait (2)
